default&#xa0;default2. defaultStrengthening relationships in the home and schooldefault&#xa0;
default2.1
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe most critical need 
defaultis the problems
default created by poor or dysfunctional relationships which leads to low levels of motivation and achievement of pupils in schools, and conflict and/or loneliness among communities, families and individuals across society (which we refer to as ‘relational povert
defaulty’). The correlation between relational breakdown in the home and poor educational outcomes is well documented. Parents from such backgrounds are often
default, 
defaultbut not exclusively
default,
default in housing and community contexts which make it hard for positive relationships to
default be sustained
default.
default&#xa0;
default2.2
default&#xa0; 
defaultE
defaultvidence from Feinstein and Symons suggests that parental involvement with education 
default(which is defined here as the amount of time and quality of an interaction with a child rather than traditional measures of engagement such as attendance a
defaultt parent/consultation evenings or participation in committees) is
default the, ‘
defaultsingle greatest predictor of achievement
default’
default; 
defaultand most importantly
default,
default factors such as the educational experience of a parent or the socio-economic context of the home 
defaultcan be
default counterbalanced by strong productive relationships. True parental engagement is 
default(perhaps) 
defaultnot with the school but with the child. Supporting and intervening in this relationship is considered vital.
default&#xa0;
default2.3
default&#xa0; 
defaultEvidence from those like Bergin and Bergin 
default(2009) 
defaultdemon
defaultstrate that students
default who develop positive relationships with teachers 
defaultachieve stronger academic outcomes.
default Where strong relationships are fostered between teachers and students, evidence suggests that poor or dysfunctional relationships in the home can be p
defaultartially compensated for
default.
default&#xa0;
default2.4
default&#xa0; 
defaultConversely, r
defaultesearch by the Centre for Social Justice 
default(2000) 
defaultsuggests that over two-thirds of all those who truanted did so in order to avoid a particular lesson, with ‘
defaultrelationship with the teacher
default’ cited as one of the principal
default grounds for relational breakdown.
default Where relationships are strong in the classroom, they can 
defaultsurmount 
defaultsocial inequality; where they are poor or dysfunctional, evidence suggests they reinforce educational disadvantage.
default&#xa0;
default2.5
default&#xa0; 
defaultPositive peer to peer relationships a
defaultlso impact on student’s academic and non-academic functioning in secondary education. Positive peer interaction correlates well with 
defaultstudent
default motivation (Furrer and Skinner, 2003), 
defaultstudent
default engagement (Keefe and Berndt, 1996) and academic 
defaultoutcomes
default (Keefe and
default Berndt, 1995).
default&#xa0;
default3. defaultPolicy defaultRecommendationsdefault&#xa0;
default3.1
default              
defaultSchools should be supported to provide more robust assessment of the relationships that sustain their performance.
default&#xa0;
default3.2
default              
defaultOfsted should review the extent to which schools are able to effectively evaluate 
defaultrelationships and identify means of improving them.
default&#xa0;
default3.3
default              
defaultGiven the importance of relationships for the provision of schooling (and other policy outcomes) the Department for Education should report on the extent to which it sees relationships as a limiting 
defaultfactor in school improvement and how such relationships might be improved.
